By Jonathan Storm<br>
Inquirer Columnist<br>
<br>
Tonight, cable's Cinemax presents a don't-miss movie that demonstrates the potential of television to inform, entertain and move its audience in ways that should make every viewer lament the lamebrained economic engine it has become.<br>
<br>
Britisher Lucy Walker saw Witness, the 1985 Harrison Ford-Kelly McGillis movie about an Amish woman caught up in a murder mystery, when she was growing up.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was fascinated,&quot; she said in a phone interview, &quot;but wasn't sure if the Amish people were bogus. In England, nobody's ever heard of them.&quot;<br>
<br>
Later on, in college, she was prepping to do an intellectual paper on communal arts. She went to a quilt exhibition. Many of the works were Amish. &quot;I immediately forgot all the theory and thought: 'Wow, they're real.' &quot;<br>
<br>
Her quest to show that reality to the rest of us began. It ends tonight with the premiere of Devil's Playground on Cinemax at 8:30.<br>
<br>
This spare, sensitive 80-minute documentary may contradict everything you thought you knew about the Amish. It will draw you into a heretofore unseen world, introducing you to young people you may never want to leave:<br>
<br>
Faron Yoder, 18, whom Walker calls &quot;an intensely honest, unself-conscious, magnificently trusting&quot; young man who wants to follow in his father's footsteps and become an Amish preacher. Unfortunately, he's also a speed-freak drug dealer.<br>
<br>
Emma Miller, a willowy 16-year-old who shares her bed with boyfriend Yoder. It's an Amish custom among dating teens called &quot;bed courtship.&quot; &quot;It's more or less condoned,&quot; an elder says, sounding like Bill Clinton. &quot;Not that they're going to have sex, but they are going to get pretty intimate.&quot;<br>
<br>
Velda Bontrager, 23, who tries on her black wedding dress for the camera. &quot;When I made it,&quot; she says, &quot;I was thinking, on the day I would get married I would feel like a queen. I don't see it like that anymore. I see it as something that covers up the girl that I really want to be.&quot;<br>
<br>
Walker's movie focuses on rumspringa, the Amish custom that lets teens loose at 16 to do whatever they want: drive fast cars, stage all-night drunken parties, even get involved with drugs. When they've had their fill, the theory goes, they will return to be baptized into the church and join the Amish way of life.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's like a vaccination,&quot; Yoder explains. &quot;You get a little dose of the outside world, just enough so you won't get tempted later on.&quot; The idea is that &quot;you'll be a happier Amish person if you had a choice.&quot;<br>
<br>
The custom has existed for most of the Amish church's 300 years. But the potential pitfalls have increased exponentially as the worldly world has speeded up and encroached ever more on the Amish world. Yet, as Walker points out at the end of Devil's Playground, almost 90 percent of Amish young people eventually join the church, the highest percentage since its founding.<br>
<br>
It took Walker two years to make the movie. Finding Amish who would agree to appear on camera was difficult, as most Amish believe photos violate the commandment against &quot;graven images.&quot;<br>
<br>
Most of the movie, which was shown at this year's Philadelphia Festival of World Cinema, was made in LaGrange County, Ind., not in Pennsylvania's more famous Lancaster County.<br>
<br>
&quot;They are so in the spotlight,&quot; she said, &quot;the barriers are a little higher between the outside world and the Lancaster communities than the others.&quot; But, she noted, most of the scenic footage comes from Lancaster. Anyone who has been there knows why.<br>
<br>
The scenery is obvious. But after this film, visitors will cast new eyes on the Amish men plowing with teams of horses, and women hanging laundry, and families clip-clopping along in those plain black buggies.<br>
<br>
The Amish, too, may draw insights about themselves from the movie, even though they have no electricity and TV is forbidden.<br>
<br>
&quot;There will be bootlegs that they'll watch on somebody's TV running off a car battery in the closet,&quot; Walker said. &quot;For a community that isn't supposed to watch movies, boy, has everyone seen Witness.&quot;<br>
<br>
